			<ns0:name>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">As Roland pointed out in http://codereview.chromium.org/7068021/ (for issue 503), if sel_ldr on Linux runs out of space in /dev/shm for dynamic code pages, it will not fail gracefully.  If sel_ldr writes to an unallocated page when /dev/shm is full, the kernel will probably kill sel_ldr with SIGBUS.

If we call posix_fallocate() on pages before filling them with HLT instructions, we can at least detect the out-of-space condition and log or return an error.
